geemap Setup in Colab#

Make sure you have the most current version of earthengine-api and geemap. (Colab has these installed by default and updates versions, but there can be lags and may not upgrade for patches). Import ee, colab, and geemap. Go through Earth Engine authentication and initialization.

!pip install --upgrade earthengine-api

!pip install --upgrade geemap

 import ee
 import geemap
 import geemap.colormaps as cm
 from google.colab import _frontend

ee.Authenticate()
ee.Initialize()

Map and console#

Add a scratch cell for the Map and console. After you run the following cell, confirm that you want to add scratch cells, and then run the “Map” cell to display the geemap.Map object (find it in the side panel to the right). We’ll add all layers to this map.

_frontend.create_scratch_cell("#@title Map\nm = geemap.Map()\nm", False)
_frontend.create_scratch_cell("#@title Console\n", False)

Vector analysis#

Let’s look at rivers in the Walla Walla Basin (Washington, USA).

  • WWF HydroSHEDS Free Flowing Rivers (lines)

  • WWF HydroATLAS Basins Level 6 (polygons)

  • Central Walla Walla, WA, USA (point)

basins = ee.FeatureCollection('WWF/HydroATLAS/v1/Basins/level06')
rivers = ee.FeatureCollection('WWF/HydroSHEDS/v1/FreeFlowingRivers')
wawa = ee.Geometry.Point([-118.3430, 46.0646])
m.set_center(-118.3430, 46.0646, 8)

# setCenter() JavaScript API
# set_center() Python

m.add_layer(basins, {'color': 'green'}, 'Level 6 basins')
m.add_layer(rivers, {'color': 'blue'}, 'Rivers')
m.add_layer(wawa, {'color': 'black'}, 'Walla Walla')
display(basins.limit(10))
display(rivers.limit(10))
display(wawa)

Filtering#

  • By attribute

  • By geometry/location

    • intersection

    • proximity

    • contained in

    • contains

By attribute#

Filter the basins feature collection to Walla Walla basin using the HYBAS_ID field. There are two options for filtering by attribute: string expressions and ee.Filter objects.

# String expression option.
wawa_basin = basins.filter('HYBAS_ID == ')
7060382460
# ee.Filter object option.
wawa_basin = basins.filter(ee.Filter.eq('HYBAS_ID', 7060382460))

m.add_layer(wawa_basin, {'color': 'yellow'}, 'Walla Walla basin')

By intersection#

Filter river segments to those that intersect Walla Walla Basin. We can use the ee.Filter.intersects method or the shorthand filterBounds method.

# ee.Filter.intersects option.
wawa_rivers = rivers.filter(
    ee.Filter.intersects(leftField='.geo', rightValue=wawa_basin.geometry(), maxError=1))

# Shorthand filterBounds option.
wawa_rivers = rivers.filterBounds(wawa_basin)

m.add_layer(wawa_rivers, {'color': 'blue'}, 'Rivers')

By proximity#

Filter rivers in Walla Walla Basin to the segments that are within 10 km of central Walla Walla.

wawa_rivers_close = rivers.filter(
    ee.Filter.withinDistance(
        distance=10e3, leftField='.geo', rightValue= wawa, maxError=1))

m.add_layer(wawa_rivers_close, {'color': 'green'}, 'Walla Walla rivers close')

Query attributes#

Let’s color the river segments by river order. We need to know the minimum and maximum stream order values for the Walla Walla rivers. Use reduceColumns to get values and statistics. The ee.Reducer.minMax() reducer returns the field’s min and max values.

wawa_rivers.reduceColumns(ee.Reducer.minMax(), ['RIV_ORD'])
    • max:8
    • min:5

Now that we know the range of river order values we can paint the vectors unto an image using a color assigned to each river order.

river_order_vis = (
    ee.Image().toByte().paint(wawa_rivers, 'RIV_ORD', 3)
    .visualize(min=5, max=8, palette=['purple', 'blue', 'lightblue', 'white'])
)

m.add_layer(river_order_vis, None, 'River order')

Let’s calculate the percentange of total Walla Walla Basin river length that is less than 7 river order (main rivers).

main_rivers = wawa_rivers.filter('RIV_ORD <= 6')
m.add_layer(main_rivers, {'color': 'orange'}, 'Main rivers')

Buffer#

Let’s make a geometry that crudely represents upland (not riparian). We’ll start by defining riparian areas as the 100 m buffer around main rivers.

riparian = main_rivers.geometry().buffer(100, 1)
m.add_layer(riparian, {'color': 'black'}, 'Main rivers buffer')

Clipping#

“Clip” the Walla Walla basin using the buffered main river geometry using the difference method.

upland = wawa_basin.geometry().difference(riparian) # get it wrong with geometry
m.add_layer(upland, {'color': 'orange'}, 'Upland')

Add a new attribute#

Let’s add a distance-to-central-Walla Walla attribute to each Walla Walla Basin river segment and then calculate the mean.

def append_distance(feature):
    distance_km = feature.distance(wawa, 1).divide(1000)
    return feature.set('distance_km', distance_km)

wawa_rivers = wawa_rivers.map(append_distance)

wawa_rivers.limit(10)

Spatial join#

Join census track info to river segments using an intersection filter with a saveFirst join.

census_tracts = ee.FeatureCollection('TIGER/2020/TRACT');
m.add_layer(census_tracts, {'color': 'purple'}, 'Census tracts')

intersect_filter = ee.Filter.intersects(leftField='.geo', rightField='.geo')
save_first_join = ee.Join.saveFirst(matchKey='tract')
wawa_rivers = save_first_join.apply(wawa_rivers, census_tracts, intersect_filter)
wawa_rivers.limit(10)

The first intersecting census tract feature is added to river segment features. It can be more convenient to copy properties from the secondary feature into the primary feature. Do it with a mapped copyProperties function.

def copy_properties(feature):
    joined_feature = feature.get('tract')
    return feature.copyProperties(joined_feature, ['TRACTCE', 'NAMELSAD'])

wawa_rivers = wawa_rivers.map(copy_properties)
wawa_rivers.limit(10)

Raster analysis#

Let’s work with a Landsat 9 TOA image collection.

Collection filtering#

Often the first step in working with image collections is to filter them to a region and period of interest. Here, we filter the Landsat collection to April-November (2023), the Walla Walla Basin region, and low cloud cover.

toa_col = (
    ee.ImageCollection('LANDSAT/LC09/C02/T1_TOA')
    .filterDate('2022-04-01', '2022-11-01')
    .filterBounds(wawa_basin)
    .filter('CLOUD_COVER < 1')
)
toa_col

Image display#

Visualize an image using parameters that select the bands for RGB and the min and max values for the color stretch.

false_color_vis = {
    'bands': ['B5', 'B4', 'B3'],
    'min': 0,
    'max': 0.4
}
m.add_layer(toa_col.first(), false_color_vis, 'TOA (first)')

Image math#

Let’s use band math to calculate NDVI and NBR. Define a function to perform the calculation so we can map the function over the image collection.

def calc_indices(image):
    # Math method chain option for NDVI.
    nir = image.select('B5')
    red = image.select('B4')
    ndvi = nir.subtract(red).divide(
        nir.add(red)).rename('ndvi')

    # String expression option for NBR.
    nbr = ee.Image().expression(
       'nbr = (nir-swir2)/(nir+swir2)',
       {
          'nir': image.select('B5'),
          'swir2': image.select('B7')
       }
    )

    # New bands are 1st and 2nd bands and then original spectal bands.
    # Empty image.select ensures that original image properties remain.
    return image.select().addBands([ndvi, nbr]).addBands(image.select('B.*'))

Function mapping#

Map the spectral index calculation function over the image collection to apply it to all of the images.

toa_col = toa_col.map(calc_indices)
band_names = toa_col.first().bandNames()
band_names

Image collection compositing#

Calculate pixel-wise max NDVI value among images in the collection (include corresponding values of the additional bands).

toa_max = toa_col.reduce(ee.Reducer.max(band_names.size())).rename(band_names)
display(toa_max)

m.add_layer(toa_max, false_color_vis, 'TOA max')

Clipping#

Clip the max NDVI composite to the Walla Walla Basin.

toa_max_basin = toa_max.clip(wawa_basin)

ndvi_vis = {
    'bands': ['ndvi'],
    'min': 0,
    'max': 0.7,
    'palette': cm.get_palette('Greens')
}
m.add_layer(toa_max_basin, ndvi_vis, 'NDVI max basin')

Zonal statistics#

Calculate median values for bands in the max NDVI composite for riparian and upland regions.

toa_riparian = toa_max_basin.reduceRegion(
    reducer=ee.Reducer.median(),
    geometry=riparian,
    scale=100,
    maxPixels=2e8
)

toa_upland = toa_max_basin.reduceRegion(
    reducer=ee.Reducer.median(),
    geometry=upland,
    scale=100,
    maxPixels=2e8
)

display('Median riparian NDVI', toa_riparian.getNumber('ndvi'))
display('Median upland NDVI', toa_upland.getNumber('ndvi'))

Sampling#

Sample 1000 random pixels from the composite. Fetch the data as a Pandas dataframe and plot a histogram and scatterplot.

toa_max_sample = toa_max_basin.sample(
    region=wawa_basin,
    scale=30,
    numPixels=1000
)

toa_max_sample.limit(10)

import pandas

df = ee.data.computeFeatures({
    'expression': toa_max_sample,
    'fileFormat': 'PANDAS_DATAFRAME'
})

df

import altair as alt

alt.Chart(df).mark_bar().encode(
    alt.X("ndvi:Q", bin=True),
    y='count()',
)

alt.Chart(df).mark_point().encode(
    x='B4:Q',
    y='B5:Q',
)
